
Here's a description of the installation options you have:

slakware:  This option installs package files to your hard drive.
           This uses up to 386 megabytes of drive space, but offers
           the best performance.  It is recommended that you use this
           option.   NOTE: If you select every software series, and
           then choose to install everything, then you'll use 386 MB.
           Hopefully you'll still have a decent amount of free space
           left over.  By the way, if you pick and choose your packages
           to any extent then you'll probably use significantly less
           space.  Installing everything puts a lot of big stuff you
           don't need on your hard drive (like X servers for display
           adaptors you don't have in your machine, etc).

slaktest:  This is the most basic test installation, and uses the
           absolute minimum drive space.  (less than 10 megabytes)
           It simply makes a link from your /usr to /cdrom/live/usr
           and runs most of the software right off the CD-ROM.  With
           modern fast CD-ROM drives, this actually doesn't work too
           badly, and since most configuration files are in /etc or
           /var you can still configure your machine completely.  

           If you decide later that you want to run Linux from your
           hard drive, you'll have to reinstall, though.  In general,
           this installation method should only be used to try out
           Linux.  C'mon, hard drives are cheap! :^)

-- end of installation method help.
